<h2 id="guidelines">Guidelines</h2>
<h3 id="types">Custom Trees</h3>
<p>The tree component can be used for displaying many different types of hierarchical information, not just a collection of links. For this reason Mdash keeps tree styles to a minimum and leaves it open for customization. Custom tree examples include:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Family tree</li>
  <li>File system</li>
  <li>Military rankings</li>
  <li>Animal taxonomy</li>
</ul>
<p>The goal is to provide a working tree component for navigation and a starting pattern for creating any other kind of tree-like UX.</p>
<h3 id="nav">Navigation Tree</h3>
<p>Put the tree inside a <code>nav</code> element when creating a navigation tree:</p>
<code-sample readonly="readonly">
  <template>
    <nav>
      <m-tree>
        ...
      </m-tree>
    </nav>
  </template>
</code-sample>
<h3 id="a11y">Accessibility</h3>
<p>Tree has <code>role="tree"</code> set automatically. You should add an <code>aria-label</code> to it. Tree items, i.e. links, summary, and other end nodes, should have <code>role="treeitem"</code>. Details elements already have the recommended <code>role="group"</code> and their <code>open</code> attribute serves the place of <code>aria-expanded</code>. Navigation trees should set <code>aria-current="page"</code> on the tree item associated with the active page and if the link is in a details element, that details should be opened. Details elements and links have built-in keyboard navigation. Here's an example:</p>
<code-sample>
  <template>
    <m-tree aria-label="My family tree">
      <details>
        <summary>
          <div role="treeitem">👨</div>
        </summary>
        <details>
          <summary>
            <div role="treeitem">👩‍🦳</div>
          </summary>
          <details>
            <summary>
              <div role="treeitem">👵</div>
            </summary>
            <div role="treeitem">💀</div>
            <div role="treeitem">💀</div>
